Motivated by the simplicity of integrating from $0$, rather than $1$, substituting $x = 1+u$ gives $$2^n\int_1^n{\frac{dx}{(1+x^2)^n}} = \int_0^{n-1}{\frac{du}{(1+u+u^2/2)^n}}.$$ We seek estimates--an upper bound and a lower bound for the integrand--that will be simple to integrate.  Dropping the "complicated" $u^2/2$ term gives one obviously integrable estimate; continuing the pattern $1+u+u^2/2 + \cdots + u^k/k! + \cdots = e^u$ leads to another.  The resulting inequalities $1 + u < 1 + u + u^2/2 < e^u$ yield (for $n \ge 1$) $$\eqalign{
\frac{1}{n}\left(1 - e^{-n(n-1)}\right) &= \int_0^{n-1}{e^{-n u}du} \cr
&\lt \int_0^{n-1}{\frac{du}{(1+u+u^2/2)^n}} \cr
&\lt \int_0^{n-1}{\frac{du}{(1+u)^n}} = \frac{1}{n-1}\left(1 - \frac{1}{n^{n-1}}\right) \cr
&\lt \frac{1}{n-1}.
}$$ Both estimates are asymptotically $1/n$, QED.
